## 1. Tables and rows

A PostgreSQL **table** stores many rows with named columns.

### Example table

```sql
CREATE TABLE books (
    title TEXT,
    author TEXT,
    pages INT
);
```

Add rows:

```sql
INSERT INTO books (title, author, pages)
VALUES
    ('Learning SQL', 'Pat Doe', 300),
    ('Science Notes', 'Maya Lee', 220);
```

Query the rows:

```sql
SELECT *
FROM books;
```

That is the closest SQL equivalent to a collection of structured records.

### Compare to Python and TypeScript

Python dictionary:

```python
book = {"title": "Learning SQL", "author": "Pat Doe", "pages": 300}
```

TypeScript object:

```ts
const book = { title: "Learning SQL", author: "Pat Doe", pages: 300 };
```

PostgreSQL row:

```sql
SELECT title, author, pages
FROM books;
```

A table is like “many objects/records of the same shape.”

